1
00:00:28,760 --> 00:00:30,480
Chanhua (wire-wrapped florals) originated in Yingshan, Hubei.

2
00:00:30,480 --> 00:00:32,560
It is a form of intangible cultural heritage,

3
00:00:32,560 --> 00:00:34,719
crafted primarily with multicolored silk threads

4
00:00:34,719 --> 00:00:37,799
wound around a frame of cardboard and copper wire,

5
00:00:37,799 --> 00:00:42,799
to create decorative works depicting birds, animals, flowers and fruit.

6
00:00:42,799 --> 00:00:44,960
The main steps of making are:

7
00:00:44,960 --> 00:00:51,399
design; cut the paper templates, trimming the shapes of leaves and petals;

8
00:00:51,399 --> 00:01:01,600
wrap the petals by winding silk thread around a copper wire frame;

9
00:01:05,439 --> 00:01:09,799
then shape and dye each petal;

10
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:17,879
and finally assemble everything into a finished piece.

11
00:01:18,840 --> 00:01:22,000
Chanhua is known for being delicate and exquisite.

12
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:26,719
It is a folk art with a long and storied history.

13
00:01:26,719 --> 00:01:30,079
Each piece carries a sculptural, three-dimensional vitality,

14
00:01:30,079 --> 00:01:33,920
earning the names "three-dimensional embroidery" and "three-dimensional craft flower."

15
00:01:33,920 --> 00:01:38,760
My own work has evolved from the traditional flat floral form

16
00:01:37,560 --> 00:01:41,680
into three-dimensional structures with a more contemporary sensibility.

17
00:01:45,200 --> 00:01:49,640
Lotus Under the Moon is one of my most representative pieces,

18
00:01:49,640 --> 00:01:55,159
blending metal wire-wrapping techniques to give the work more vitality.

19
00:01:55,159 --> 00:02:00,519
It also marked the beginning of a new stylistic phase for me.

20
00:02:00,519 --> 00:02:04,959
In this piece I designed a copper wire floral earring form,

21
00:02:04,959 --> 00:02:09,599
and applied copper wire edging and hand-dyeing to the lotus petals.

22
00:02:11,000 --> 00:02:15,919
It is no longer a flat flower, it is a fully three-dimensional form.

23
00:02:15,919 --> 00:02:21,680
Especially in the curve of each petal rising from the base,

24
00:02:21,680 --> 00:02:27,960
there is a feeling of upward growth, mimicking the way plants reach toward the sky.

25
00:02:30,199 --> 00:02:38,000
Art must be rooted in nature, yet it must transcend it.

26
00:02:38,000 --> 00:02:43,360
After moving in this direction, I wanted to introduce some abstract elements.

27
00:02:43,360 --> 00:02:50,400
Spring Water was my attempt, to bring a sense of fluid movement into the tassel work.

28
00:02:50,400 --> 00:02:57,400
I thought of Wu Guanzhong's paintings, those black, white, and green visions of Jiangnan.

29
00:02:57,400 --> 00:03:08,400
By adding touches of black and white into the green tassels, the whole composition comes alive.

30
00:03:08,400 --> 00:03:14,000
Beyond color, I also introduced geometric and abstract structural forms.

31
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:21,400
The tassels carry not just color, they also move: hanging, floating, flowing.

32
00:03:21,400 --> 00:03:26,000
So I used tassels of different forms to express that sense of movement.

33
00:03:27,599 --> 00:03:31,599
Having practiced for several years now, I believe the most important quality is perseverance.

34
00:03:31,599 --> 00:03:36,599
More important, even, than talent or natural ability.

35
00:03:36,599 --> 00:03:42,599
Because we all go through periods of invisibility, when no one notices the work.

36
00:03:42,599 --> 00:03:48,599
But rather than chasing external recognition, we must always return to our own world.

37
00:03:48,599 --> 00:03:54,599
For the very act of continuing, of showing up day after day, is what moves people.

